2. Develop a one hidden layer multi-layer perceptron model on the above training data, report the accuracy of the model.¶

In [11]:
# Preprocess the data
train_images = train_images.reshape((train_images.shape[0], 28 * 28)).astype('float32') / 255
test_images = test_images.reshape((test_images.shape[0], 28 * 28)).astype('float32') / 255

# Convert labels to one-hot encoding
train_labels = to_categorical(train_labels, 10)
test_labels = to_categorical(test_labels, 10)

# Build the model
model = Sequential()
model.add(Dense(128, activation='relu', input_shape=(28 * 28,)))
model.add(Dense(10, activation='softmax'))

# Compile the model
model.compile(optimizer=Adam(), loss='categorical_crossentropy', metrics=['accuracy'])

# Train the model
history=model.fit(train_images, train_labels, epochs=10, batch_size=128, validation_split=0.2, verbose=2)

# Evaluate the model
test_loss, test_accuracy = model.evaluate(test_images, test_labels, verbose=2)
print(f'Test accuracy: {test_accuracy:.4f}')

3. From question 2, set the number of hidden layers of the MLP model as [2,4,6,8,10], set the hidden layer size as 100, show the accuracies on the test set.¶

  • Observation: Despite the increasing number of hidden layers, the test accuracy of the model remains around 97%
In [14]:
# Define the number of hidden layers to test
hidden_layer_counts = [2, 4, 6, 8, 10]
hidden_layer_size = 100

# Initialize lists to store results
test_accuracies = []
computation_times = []

# Loop through the different numbers of hidden layers
for num_hidden_layers in hidden_layer_counts:
    # Build the model
    model = Sequential()
    model.add(Dense(hidden_layer_size, activation='relu', input_shape=(28 * 28,)))
    
    # Add the specified number of hidden layers with size 100
    for _ in range(num_hidden_layers):
        model.add(Dense(hidden_layer_size, activation='relu'))
    
    model.add(Dense(10, activation='softmax'))

    # Compile the model
    model.compile(optimizer=Adam(), loss='categorical_crossentropy', metrics=['accuracy'])

    # Measure the time taken to train and evaluate the model
    start_time = time.time()
    model.fit(train_images, train_labels, epochs=10, batch_size=128, validation_split=0.2, verbose=0)
    test_loss, test_accuracy = model.evaluate(test_images, test_labels, verbose=0)
    end_time = time.time()

    # Append results
    test_accuracies.append(test_accuracy)
    computation_times.append(end_time - start_time)

# Plotting the results
fig, ax1 = plt.subplots()

# Plot test accuracy vs number of hidden layers
ax1.plot(hidden_layer_counts, test_accuracies, 'o-', color='blue', label='Test Accuracy')
ax1.set_xlabel('Number of Hidden Layers')
ax1.set_ylabel('Test Accuracy', color='blue')
ax1.tick_params(axis='y', labelcolor='blue')

# Create a second y-axis for computation time
ax2 = ax1.twinx()
ax2.plot(hidden_layer_counts, computation_times, 's-', color='red', label='Computation Time')
ax2.set_ylabel('Computation Time (seconds)', color='red')
ax2.tick_params(axis='y', labelcolor='red')

plt.title('Model Performance with 100 Neurons per Hidden Layer')
plt.show()

4. From question 2, for the hidden layer set the hidden layer size as [50, 100, 150, 200], show the accuracies on the test set.¶

In [15]:
# Define the hidden layer sizes to test
hidden_layer_sizes = [50, 100, 150, 200]

# Initialize lists to store results
test_accuracies = []
computation_times = []

# Loop through the different hidden layer sizes
for hidden_layer_size in hidden_layer_sizes:
    # Build the model
    model = Sequential()
    model.add(Dense(hidden_layer_size, activation='relu', input_shape=(28 * 28,)))
    model.add(Dense(10, activation='softmax'))

    # Compile the model
    model.compile(optimizer=Adam(), loss='categorical_crossentropy', metrics=['accuracy'])

    # Measure the time taken to train and evaluate the model
    start_time = time.time()
    model.fit(train_images, train_labels, epochs=10, batch_size=128, validation_split=0.2, verbose=0)
    test_loss, test_accuracy = model.evaluate(test_images, test_labels, verbose=0)
    end_time = time.time()

    # Append results
    test_accuracies.append(test_accuracy)
    computation_times.append(end_time - start_time)

# Plotting the results
fig, ax1 = plt.subplots()

# Plot test accuracy vs hidden layer size
ax1.plot(hidden_layer_sizes, test_accuracies, 'o-', color='blue', label='Test Accuracy')
ax1.set_xlabel('Hidden Layer Size')
ax1.set_ylabel('Test Accuracy', color='blue')
ax1.tick_params(axis='y', labelcolor='blue')

# Create a second y-axis for computation time
ax2 = ax1.twinx()
ax2.plot(hidden_layer_sizes, computation_times, 's-', color='red', label='Computation Time')
ax2.set_ylabel('Computation Time (seconds)', color='red')
ax2.tick_params(axis='y', labelcolor='red')

plt.title('Model Performance with Varying Hidden Layer Sizes')
plt.show()
  • Observation: Despite the increasing number of hidden layers size , the test accuracy of the model remains constant

5. Based on question 3 and 4, explain the key findings¶

  • When varying the number of hidden layers or the size of hidden layers in a multi-layer perceptron (MLP) model, the test accuracy was almost constant to 97%

  • Increasing the size of a hidden layer allows the model to learn a richer set of features, which can improve performance up to a point, which has not really been the case in our model.

  • As with increasing the number of layers, larger hidden layers can lead to overfitting if the model becomes too complex relative to the amount of training data.

  • Larger hidden layers mean more parameters to train, which has slightly increased the computational resources required and extend the training time, it took a bit more time to get the all outputs.

  • Single Hidden Layer with Optimal Size: For many tasks, a single hidden layer with an appropriately chosen size can perform very well, especially on datasets like MNIST that are not excessively complex.
